XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two-vehicle crash occurred at a 4-way intersection during morning hours on a dry, overcast weekday. The north/south roadway was divided by a raised grass median. The northbound side had four lanes including a left turn lane to the westbound roadway. Southbound traffic had three lanes. The westbound roadway was undivided and had four lanes: one left turn-only, one straight, one right turn-only, and one lane for eastbound traffic. The posted speed limit for all directions was 72 kmph (45 mph). The roads were bituminous and level in all directions.
Vehicle 1 was a 1998 Chevrolet Blazer sport utility vehicle with two occupants traveling north. Vehicle 2 was a 2000 Chevrolet C-3500 pickup towing a 5000 lb. trencher on a trailer. V2 had two occupants and was stopped for a red light facing west. V2's light changed to green and the driver of V2 proceeded into the intersection with the intention of going straight across. V1 failed to stop for a red light and the front of V1 struck the left side of V2. V1 rotated in a counterclockwise direction and the right rear side of V1 struck the trencher on V2's trailer. V2 overturned 1-quarter turn onto the passenger side. The trailer did not overturn. V1 and V2 came to final rest side-by-side facing northwest.
The Chevy Blazer (V1) was driven by a 34-year old female who was transported from the scene with possible injuries. According to the police report, the driver of V1 stated that she was talking to her son, who was in the back seat. She was also looking at him, and when she looked up, she was in the middle of the intersection. It wasn't until she looked up that she noticed the light in her direction was red. Police estimated her speed to have been 56 kmph (35 mph) at impact. Her vehicle was towed from the scene due to disabling front end damage.
The Critical Pre-crash Event for V1 was "other motor vehicle encroachment from crossing street, across path." The Critical Reason for the Critical Event was not coded to V1; however, several associated factors were coded to the driver of V1. First of all, there was an internal distraction. The driver stated she was looking back at her son and not paying attention to the road or traffic control signals. She was focused on her son and did not look at the traffic signal until it was too late (inadequate surveillance). She was also talking to her son. An illegal maneuver was also coded because the driver of V1 failed to stop for a red light. No other associated factors are known for this driver because she could not be reached for an interview.
The Chevy C-3500 (V2) was driven by a 59-year old man who worked full time burying cables. He reported possible injuries and was transported from the scene for treatment. He was on his way to the hardware store to pick up supplies when the crash occurred. He reported being stopped at the red light. He thinks there was a brown SUV in lane 3 making a left turn that may have obstructed his view of V1. The driver of V2 proceeded into the intersection when the light turned green and was hit suddenly on the driver's side door. He claimed to have not seen V1 coming from the left. He took no avoidance maneuvers. He estimated his speed to be 23 kmph (15 mph) at impact. His vehicle was towed from the scene due to disabling left side damage.
The Critical Pre-crash Event for V2 was "this vehicle traveling - crossing over (passing through) intersection." The Critical Reason for the Critical Event was coded as "inadequate surveillance," because the driver of V2 failed to look for any approaching traffic before entering the intersection. The driver reportedly drove this roadway daily and was very comfortable with the handling of his vehicle. He reported feeling tired in the morning when he wakes up for work, but wasn't tired at the time of the crash. The driver was listening to the radio and talking to his stepson in the passenger's seat at the time of the crash. The conversation was coded as an associated factor, as was a sightline restriction caused by the non-contact vehicle in the adjacent westbound lane that may have blocked Driver 2's view of V1.
